<h2>A Living Relationship</h2>

<p>Perhaps the most important thing to understand about the Eastern approach to the saints is that it is not historical. The saints are not in the past. They are more alive now than they were on earth, because death, for those who have been united to the Risen Christ, is not an ending but a transition. The Church prays <em>with</em> the saints, not merely <em>about</em> them.</p>

<p>This is why an Eastern Christian will ask St. Nicholas to pray for them with the same naturalness as asking a living friend. It is why relics, the physical remains of the saints, are venerated with such reverence: the body that was a temple of the Holy Spirit in life does not cease to be holy in death. It is why the saints' icons are kissed, their troparion sung, their stories told and retold.</p>

<p>The saints are not a monument to past achievement. They are ongoing proof that grace works, that theosis is real, that the God who transformed a tax collector into an evangelist and a persecutor into an apostle is still in the business of making saints. Today, now, out of the most unlikely material.</p>

<p>Including, the Church dares to hope, out of you.</p>

<p>The beliefs, practices, and lived spirituality of Eastern Christianity have now been explored. The next step turns to a harder question: why is the Christian East divided from the Christian West, and what hope is there for reunion?</p>

